That's right!  J is the hypoglossal nerve, CN XII. Note that the hypoglossal nerve swings superficial to the carotid arteries, then disappears deep to the posterior belly of the digastric muscle and the lateral border of the mylohyoid muscle to enter the floor of the mouth.

IDENTIFY the posterior belly of the digastric and stylohyoid muscle.
By palpation, identify the tip of the greater horn of the hyoid bone. Between the tip of the hyoid and the posterior belly of the digastric, identify and outline the hypoglossal nerve.

Clean it carefully and observe that the nerve sweeps inferior to the posterior belly of the digastric, crossing the external carotid     artery before it passes medial to the digastric and enters the mouth deep to the mylohyoid muscle.
